        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Corpus Christi, TX: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Corpus Christi, TX, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Corpus Christi Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the International Fire Code (IFC) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Corpus Christi Fire Extinguisher Inspection Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Corpus Christi enforces the International Fire Code (IFC), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Four inspection intervals apply to every commercial extinguisher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Corpus Christi's Gulf Coast location creates unique fire extinguisher maintenance challenges. Salt air corrosion accelerates degradation of extinguisher cylinder hardware and mounting brackets — coastal commercial properties should inspect monthly for corrosion damage and replace units more frequently than inland facilities. The commercial landscape spans waterfront restaurants and hotels, port-adjacent industrial facilities, Southside retail corridors, and North Padre Island hospitality operations.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by your own trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, the tamper seal is intact, and the pull pin is in place. Document every monthly check. In the event of a fire incident or an enforcement action, the absence of monthly records significantly increases your liability exposure.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle integrity, and overall unit condition — then attaches a dated service tag. In Texas, fire extinguisher service must be performed by a technician licensed through the Texas Department of Insurance (TDI) State Fire Marshal's Office under a Portable Fire Extinguisher license. Verify licensing at tdi.texas.gov/fire before scheduling service. Any unit that fails must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation that external inspections miss. This typically includes a complete recharge. Missing the 6-year exam is a frequently cited violation during Corpus Christi Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must undergo hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned. After passing, units are recharged and marked with the new test date. Plan for some units to require replacement at the 12-year mark — budget accordingly.</p>

